What Happens Here?

The charger continuously generates a 1 kHz PWM waveform with amplitudes of +12 V and -12 V.

The signal travels through the CP conductor into the vehicle.

The EV modifies the signal by connecting different resistor combinations between CP and Protective Earth (PE).

The charger continuously measures the resulting voltage using an ADC connected to its MCU.

Based on the measured voltage, the charger determines the current charging state.
Why Does IEC 61851 Use ±12V Instead of Only +12V?

Many engineers assume the CP line is only used for current advertisement.

In reality, the negative half cycle provides an additional safety mechanism.

Positive Half Cycle

Used for:

Vehicle detection
State identification
PWM current advertisement
Negative Half Cycle

Used for:

Diode verification
Cable integrity check
CP fault detection

If the charger does not detect the expected negative response, charging is immediately prohibited.

This prevents charging with damaged cables or faulty vehicle interfaces.
