📡 PWM Communication

The voltage state identifies the vehicle condition.

The PWM duty cycle advertises the maximum current available from the charger.

Current Advertisement Formula

For duty cycles between 10% and 85%:

Maximum Current (A)

Imax = Duty Cycle (%) × 0.6
Examples
Duty Cycle	Available Current
10%	6 A
20%	12 A
30%	18 A
50%	30 A
60%	36 A
80%	48 A
85%	51 A
🔄 Complete Charging Sequence
Step 1 – Idle State
CP = +12V

State A

No vehicle detected.

Step 2 – Vehicle Plugged In
CP = +9V

State B

Vehicle presence confirmed.

Step 3 – EV Requests Charging
CP = +6V

State C

Vehicle ready to receive power.

Step 4 – Contactor Closure

EVSE detects State C.

Contactor → CLOSED

AC power becomes available.

Step 5 – Current Negotiation

PWM duty cycle is transmitted.

Example:

Duty Cycle = 50%

Vehicle calculates:

Maximum Current = 30A
Step 6 – Active Charging

Charging continues while CP is continuously monitored.

Any unexpected transition:

6V → 9V

or

6V → 12V

causes immediate charging termination.

🔍 Troubleshooting Guide (NOC Engineer Perspective)
Observation	Possible Root Cause
CP stuck at +12V	Vehicle not detected
CP stuck at +9V	EV not requesting charge
CP stuck at +6V	Contactor or power stage issue
No negative pulse	Missing diode or cable fault
CP oscillates 9V ↔ 6V	Loose connector
Sudden jump to 12V	Vehicle unplugged
Wrong PWM duty cycle	Configuration mismatch
🎯 Key Takeaways

✅ CP is the first communication channel established between EV and EVSE.

✅ Voltage level indicates vehicle state.

✅ PWM duty cycle indicates available current.

✅ Negative half cycle is used for safety validation.

✅ Charging is only permitted in State C.

✅ CP monitoring remains active throughout the charging session.

